This one is for our FL Studio gang! ⁣
⁣
This stock FL Studio plugin lets you see which notes are being played in complicated audio material. It doesn’t work on everything, but it can be very helpful in studying chords, vocals, and other tonal samples!⁣
⁣
Also helpful for figuring out the key of your samples!⁣
⁣
If this one helps, share with an FL Studio friend!⁣

To some, this might be laughable...DONT HATE! There was a day where YOU didn't know this!⁣
⁣
⁣
Are you in the process of LEARNING scales? This helps.⁣
⁣
⁣
It's hard when you start anything for the first time and this trick absolutely ease the process!⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣
⁣
Creating a song in a certain scale (e.g. Gminor)? Look up which notes are in that scale and place stickers on all of those keys, across the octaves. This will now clearly show you which keys you can press to stay in that scale.⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣
⁣
This should allow you to have more confidence when "jamming out," which is EXTREMELY important.  It's hard to just pencil in melodies all the time. Many of the best creations come from mistakes, and experimentation. These markers will allow you to do just that, and keep you under control and in key!⁣
⁣
⁣
*Some DAW's have a feature which will allow you to stay in the scale (even if you play a "wrong" note). These are cool, but they don't actually teach you which notes are correct while playing :(

node.accessibility_caption: Are you making this common eq mistake while producing?
Should every sound have its own space in the mix?
This is 100% true but we need to understand how this applies to EQ
Steep filters and eq shapes look good but sound unnatural
Think of an orchestra.  There is plenty of overlap
Volume is the mixing tool we use to separate competing sounds
Steep filter shapes can sound unnatural.  They are hard to fit sounds together
Use gradual filter shapes.  Choose sounds that compliment each other rather than overlap.
Steep slopes can be used in mastering or group processing.
Hope this helps
